In this proclamation, President Barack Obama declares September 2016 as National Childhood Cancer Awareness Month. The proclamation highlights the significance of childhood cancer and the need for continued research and advancements in treatment. It emphasizes the improvements made in survival rates over the years but acknowledges the challenges faced by survivors. The proclamation discusses the initiatives taken by the administration, such as the Gabriella Miller Kids First Research Act and the Precision Medicine Initiative, to invest in pediatric cancer research. It also mentions the White House Cancer Moonshot Task Force, led by Vice President Joe Biden, which aims to make significant progress in preventing, diagnosing, and treating cancer. The Affordable Care Act is mentioned as a means to provide quality and affordable healthcare to children with cancer. The proclamation calls for raising awareness about childhood cancer and encourages individuals, organizations, and agencies to participate in activities that promote prevention and awareness.